[[Image:Une guelta, près d'Oubankort dans l'Adrar des Ifoghas.jpg|thumb|A guelta, close to [[Oubankort]] in [[Adrar des Ifoghas]].]] [[File:GueltaCamels.jpg|thumb|Camels in the [[Guelta d'Archei]], in north-eastern [[Chad]].]]
A '''guelta''' ({{lang-ar|قلتة}}, also transliterated '''qalta''' or '''galta'''; [[Berber languages|Berber]]: '''agelmam''') is a pocket of water that forms in drainage canals or [[wadis]] in the [[Sahara]].<ref name=likens>{{cite book |url=https://encrypted.google.com/books?id=OzJOqh90RuwC&pg=PA269 |title=Lake Ecosystem Ecology: A Global Perspective |publisher=Academic Press |editor=Gene E. Likens |year=2010 |page=269 |accessdate=June 5, 2014|isbn=9780123820037 }}</ref> The size and duration will depend on the location and conditions. It may last year-round through the dry season if fed by a source such as a spring.<ref name=likens/> When a river (wadi) dries up, there may be pockets of water remaining along its course (c.f. [[ox-bow lake]]).<ref name=likens/> In Western Sahara, gueltas correspond with [[oases]].<ref name=likens/>
Some examples include [[Guelta d'Archei]] in [[Chad]] and [[Timia]] in [[Niger]].
