{{Infobox laboratory |name = Rowland Institute for Science |motto = |image = Rowland Institute at Harvard - Cambridge, MA - DSC05660.JPG |established = 1980 |director = [[Cynthia Friend]] |city = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[United States]] |budget = |type = Experimental science |staff = |campus = |nobel_laureates = |operating_agency = [[Harvard University]] |website = {{URL|http://www2.rowland.harvard.edu/}} }} The '''Rowland Institute for Science''' was founded by [[Edwin H. Land]], founder of [[Polaroid Corporation]], as a nonprofit, privately endowed basic research organization in 1980. It is named for the first head of the [[American Physical Society]], [[Henry Augustus Rowland]]. The Rowland is dedicated to experimental science across a wide range of disciplines. Research subjects at the institute includes chemistry, physics and biology, and focuses on interdisciplinary work and the development of new experimental tools.
The institute merged with [[Harvard University]] on July 1, 2002, and is now called ''The 'Rowland Institute at Harvard'''. It is located near [[Kendall Square]] in Cambridge, Massachusetts, and is a few miles away from the main campus.
==Rowland Junior Fellows== The flagship program at the Rowland Institute is the Junior Fellowship.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rowland Institute at Harvard - Sponsor Information on GrantForward {{!}} Search for federal grants, foundation grants, and limited submission opportunities|url=https://www.grantforward.com/sponsor/detail/rowland-institute-at-harvard-10055|website=Grant Forward|accessdate=11 April 2017|language=en|date=26 October 2016}}</ref> The program serves as a [[postdoctoral]] research program for early career [[experiment|experimental]] scientists.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=von Bubnoff|first1=Andreas|title=Superpostdocs Reach for the Stars|journal=Cell|date=23 March 2007|volume=128|issue=6|pages=1023–1026|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0092867407003169|accessdate=11 April 2017|doi=10.1016/j.cell.2007.03.005}}</ref> Fellows receive funding for salary and research expenses and are allocated their own [[laboratory]] space. The Rowland Institute also provides technical support from permanent staff. The Fellowship lasts for five years, with continuation past three years contingent on a favorable internal review.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rowland Institute at Harvard -- Rowland Junior Fellows|url=https://researchfunding.duke.edu/rowland-institute-harvard-rowland-junior-fellows|website=Research Funding|publisher=Duke University|accessdate=12 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>
==Notable members and alumni== *[[Howard Berg]] - biophysicist noted for his work on the [[motility]] of the bacterium [[Escherichia coli]] (E. coli) *[[Steven Block]] - pioneered the use of [[optical tweezers]] to study step dynamics of [[kinesin]] and [[RNA polymerase]] on DNA templates *[[Colleen Cavanaugh]] - microbiologist recognized for her studies of [[hydrothermal vent]] ecosystems *[[Donald A. Glaser]] - physicist, neurobiologist, and winner of the 1960 [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] for inventing the [[bubble chamber]] *[[Jene Golovchenko]] - physicist noted for his work on materials for [[whole genome sequencing]] *[[Lene Hau]] - physicist noted for her work on [[Bose–Einstein condensate]], and ultracold atomic system optics *[[Winfield Hill]] - co-authored the popular text ''[[The Art of Electronics]]'' with Harvard Physicist [[Paul Horowitz]]
==Past Directors== *[[Edwin H. Land]]: 1980 - 1992 *[[Phil Dubois]]: 1992 - 1997 *Michael Burns: 1998 - 2002 *[[Frans Spaepen]]: 2002 - 2013 *[[Cynthia Friend]]: 2013 - present
